Minute Entry for proceedings held before US Magistrate Judge Camille L. Velez- Rive:Initial Appearance as to Manuel D. Collazo-Lopez, John Murphy-Cordero, Ariel Fuentes-Ortiz, Miguel A. Gonzalez-Gonzalez, David Robles-Quiles, Jose De-Leon- Serrano, Wilfredo Vazquez-Lopez, Luis J. Perez-Delgado, Emanuel J. Vazquez-Rivera, Ricardo A. Lozada-Molina held on 9/22/2011. Defendants were provided with copy of the indictment and advised as to the charges and their rights. At the request of the US Probation Office and with the approval of the Presiding Judge, the Court granted waiving the financial affidavits at this time. If needed, and at the request be it from the Government or Probation, the CJA-23 forms will be filled at the time of the arraignments. US Probation also provided the Court with the pertinent financial information as to each defendant. A member of the CJA Panel will be appointed to represent each of the defendants. Arraignment/Detention hearings set for 9/27/2011 at 09:00 AM in Courtroom 11 before US Magistrate Judge Camille L. Velez-Rive. Defendants are ordered detained pending hearings. (yr) (Entered: 09/26/2011)

Present: SAUSA Alberto Lopez and attorney Raul S. Mariani. Defendant is present and assisted by the Court Interpreter. Defendant was found competent to understand the proceedings. Defendant waived the reading of the Indictment and entered a plea of not guilty as to all counts. Case is referred to Judge Jose A. Fuste for trial setting. As to bail, defense counsel informs he has no evidence to rebut the presumptions and findings in the PTS Report. However, reserves right to re-open the bail issue. Government's proffer heard and requests detention. Certified Copy of Order from USCA as to Junior J. Nieves-Rivera re: 984 Notice of Appeal - Final Judgment; We note that, in the plea agreement, the defendant and the government agreed to recommend to the sentencing judge that the federal sentence run concurrently with specified sentences imposed by a Commonwealth court. At the very brief sentencing hearing, however, neither party expressly called this provision to the sentencing court's attention, and sentence was imposed without the sentencing judge addressing concurrency. Since the default rule is that "[mJultiple terms of imprisonment imposed at different times run consecutively unless the court orders that the terms are to run concurrently, 18 U.S.C. § 3584(a), the effect of silence is that the federal sentence runs consecutively to the Commonwealth sentences. We ask the sentencing judge to clarify whether consecutive sentences was the judge's intention and to transmit his answer in writing to this court. (xi) (Entered: 01/23/2013)

Minute Entry for proceedings held before Judge Jose A. Fuste: Re-sentencing as to Jorge Aviles-Santiago (20) held on 4/28/2014. Present: AUSA Alberto R. Lopez, Atty. Raymond L. Sanchez, USPO Deni Rodriguez. Defendant is U/C and present in court. USCA remanded the case for re-sentencing. Defense counsel presented the testimony of Carmen M. Santiago-De Hoyos, defendant's mother, on behalf of the defendant. Cross- examination by AUSA. Re-direct. Defendant's allocution heard. Arguments presented by each party. Defendant's request for a variance was denied as argued in 1299 Motion to Reduce Sentence. However, taking into account the testimony presented by the defendant, the Court granted a 2-point reduction based on 3553 factors. Count 1, IMPR for 60 months; SRT of 8 years; SMA of $100.00. Defendant was advised of his right to appeal. Attorney Sanchez shall file a voucher for a transcript of this proceeding. Exhibit admitted: Government's 1. REPORT AND RECOMMENDATION as to Joel Marrero-Marrero (36). During the preliminary revocation hearing for violations of supervised release, the Defendant accepted the allegations contained in the motion by USPO at Docket. No. 1722 , except the one pertaining to new criminal conduct. The Defendant argued that the domestic violence charges were dismissed, therefore, no violation to Statutory Condition No.1 was committed. The Court needed to determine if the underlying conduct that gave rise to the dismissed charges could violate Standard Condition No.1. The parties proffered to the Court the recordings of conversations between the defendant and his partner, as well as copies of the text messages between them. After reviewing the text messages and listening to the recordings the court finds that there was no threat amounting to what can be construed as domestic violence. The defendant and his partner offended one another, were disrespectful towards one another and used foul language on both sides. I do not find probable cause to violate the defendant on the violation of Standard Condition No. 1. Signed by US Magistrate Judge Silvia Carreno-Coll on 09/18/2017.(Carreno-Coll, Silvia) (Entered: 09/18/2017)

ORDER as to Pablo J. Figueroa-Vazquez (27). A preliminary revocation hearing was held today in relation to Docket Nos. 1890 and 1901 in which USPO Norman Rosario testified. Minutes will follow. Just before starting the cross-examination, defense counsel requested the chronological notes under Fed.R.Crim.P. 26.2. A review of the docket shows that the request was not done prior to the hearing. The request was orally denied without prejudice and the undersigned herein amplifies the reasons for the denial. Rule 26.2 only applies to statements in the government's possession, and the government does not have the probation officer's chronological notes as they are confidential records which were prepared by the probation officer for use in carrying out her duties as a member of the judiciary, not as an arm of the government or part of the prosecution. See United States v. Rivera-Rodrguez, 321 F.Supp. 3d 278 (D.P.R. 2018) (" [t]he probation officer's chronological notes undisputedly constitute confidential records which [are] prepared by the probation officer for the use in carrying out [his or] her duties as a member of the judiciary, not as an arm of the prosecution."); United States v. Rockot, 2013 WL 5536224 (W.D. Pa. 2013) (unpublished, same); United States v. Houston, 2009 WL 2488176 at *53 (E.D.Cal., 2009) (unpublished, the chrono notes [of a probation officer] are not in the government's constructive possession and so are not subject to production under Federal Rule of Criminal Procedure 26.2"); United States v. Washington, 146 F.3d 219, 223 (4th Cir. 1998) ("[A] probation officer... [is a] neutral, information-gathering agent of the court, not an agent of the prosecution."); United States v. Ritter, 45 Fed.Appx, 609 (unpublished) (Due process did not require the government to produce the probation officer's notes because the notes were not used as evidence against Ritter. See United States v. Donaghe, 924 F.2d 940, 944 (9th Cir. 1991). Further, lack of access to the notes did not compromise Ritter's rights under the confrontation clause to a fair and meaningful opportunity to refute or impeach the evidence against him. See United States v. Martin, 984 F.2d 308, 310 (9th Cir. 1993).'"). The undersigned sees no reason to deviate from the above under the circumstances of this case at this stage. Defendant was advised that he may file a motion requesting the chronological notes to the presiding District Judge for her to consider the request prior to the final revocation hearing. Signed by US Magistrate Judge Camille L. Velez-Rive on 6/17/2019. (evr) (Entered: 06/17/2019)

Minute Entry for proceedings held before US Magistrate Judge Camille L. Velez-Rive: Initial Appearance re Revocation of Supervised Release and Show Cause Hearing as to Pablo J. Figueroa-Vazquez (27) held via VTC on 11/10/2020. Present were AUSA Ginette Milanes, AFPD Cherrelle Herbert and USPO Linda Perez. The defendant was present by video and assisted by a certified court interpreter. The defendant voluntarily waived his right to be physically present at the hearing and consented to the holding of the hearing via VTC. The defendant was advised of the SRT violations contained in 2052 Motion Notifying Violations of Supervision Conditions and as to his rights. Defense counsel stated that the allegations contained in the motion presented by USPO will not be contested at this time and requested that the defendant be allowed to remain under the same conditions of release pending further proceedings. The government did not object. The Court ordered the defendant to remain under the same conditions of release pending the final revocation hearing and strongly urged the defendant to comply with the SRT conditions. The case was referred to U.S. District Judge Aida Delgado- Colon. Pursuant to the Due Process Protections Act, the Court confirms the United States obligation to produce all exculpatory evidence to the defendant pursuant to Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83 (1963) and its progeny, and orders it to do so. Failing to do so in a timely manner may result in consequences, including, but not limited to, exclusion of evidence, adverse jury instructions, dismissal of charges, contempt proceedings, or sanctions by the Court. (Court Reporter DCR.) Hearing set for 10:30AM. Hearing held at 10:31AM. Hearing ended at 10:37AM. Interpreter Carlos Ravelo. (ecc) Modified typographical error on 11/12/2020 (idg). (Entered: 11/10/2020)
